Introduction¶

The objective of this case study is to assist the sellers, buyers, in the used car market. Based on the information provided by the users, it may then provide a relatively accurate price estimate, understand what are all the attribute feature effect on the price of a car, selecting the right features which plays a significant role in predicting the price of a car. The dataset for automobile prices utilised in the study was obtained from kaggle. This dataset contains automobile pricing from year 1939 until 2020. The descriptive feature include This dataset has 17 features and 19237 observations in total. Target variable is continous numeric variable.

Phase 1 Summary ¶

In Phase 1 project we deployed several data cleaning, preprocessing, and data visualisation techniques. we chose to remove extraneous columns, namely ID variables. So we chose to partition our dataset into two categories of variables: category and numerical variables, and then conduct our analysis. We also evaluated our dataset for missing data, outliers, and imbalance, and we opted to eliminate any rows with such data quality concerns. Because the data appeared to be quite clean to begin with, cleaning was minimal. Moreover, we used a correlations matrix to better assess the strength of the association between distinct factors.

We created numerous visualisations to analyse the data using the explanatory factors. It was apparent that the majority of people like to buy sedan vehicles, followed by jeep and hatchback cars in black, silver, and white, and that the prefered fuel type is petrol, followed by diesel and hybrid.

We also noticed that several of the numerical statistics, such as the goal variables and pricing, are skewed. To overcome this issue, data scaling/transformation will be required. We've seen that tax, fuel type, colour, and category type all play important roles in determining automobile prices.

We will expand on the work done in Phase 1 to better prepare the dataset for analysis and modelling in Phase 2. We will concentrate on encoding category variables into numeric variables and scaling the numerical variables to ensure they are all on the same scale.

This will allow us to apply a broader set of statistical analysis and machine learning techniques to the information in order to find the primary factors influencing automotive costs. We will also obtain a better grasp of the correlations between factors such as tax, fuel type, colour, and category type, as well as how these affect automotive pricing.

We can construct more accurate pricing models by undertaking a more extensive investigation. by dealerships and customers to make better informed judgements while purchasing or selling automobiles. Overall, the Phase 2 project will expand on the work completed in Phase 1 to allow for more sophisticated analysis and modelling, resulting in more accurate and actionable findings.

Overview Of Methodology¶

We consider the following regression model to predict our target feature:

    1) KNN Regressor

    2) Decision Tree

    3) Random Forest Regressor

    4) Regression Models (Linear, Ridige, Lasso)

Our modeling strategy begins by transforming the full dataset cleaned in Phase 1. This transformation includes encoding categorical descriptive features as numerical and then scaling of the descriptive features. We first randomly sample 5K rows from the full dataset and then split this sample into training and test sets with a 70:30 ratio. This way, our training data has 3.5K and test data has 1.5K. To be clear, our terminology here is that

    1) The 3.5K rows of data used during the hyper parameter tuning phase is 
       called the training data.

    2) The 1.5K rows of data used during the performance comparison phase is 
       called the test data.

Before fitting a particular classifier on the training data, we select the best feature using the powerful Random Forest Importance method inside a pipeline. we have search over 10, 20, and the full set of 17 features to determine which number of features works best with each classifier. Using feature selection together with hyper-parameter search inside a single pipline, we conduct a RepeatedStratified cross-validation to fine-tune hyper-parameters of each regressor using R2 and MAE as the performance metric. We build each model using parallel processing with "-2" cores. We also examine sensitivity of each model with respect to its hyperparameters during the search.

Regressor with the best set of hyper-parameter values as identified via grid search using the training data are called tuned Regressor. Once we identify the Four tuned Regressor( with the best hyper-parameter values), we 'fit' them on the test data using cross-validation in a paired fashion and we perform paired t-tests to see if any performance difference is statistically significant. In addition, we are comparing the regressor wit respect to their r2 and MAE scores and confusion matrices on the test data.

plt.style.use("ggplot")

def plot_imp(best_features, scores, method_name):
    plt.barh(best_features, scores)
    plt.title(method_name + ' Feature Importances')
    plt.xlabel("Importance")
    plt.ylabel("Features")
    plt.show()

K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN)¶

Using pipeline, we stack feature selection and grid search for KNN hyperparameter tuning via cross-validation. We will use same pipline methodology for Decision Tree, RandomForestRegressor and Linear Regressor model.

The KNN hyperparameters are as follows:

1) number of neighbors (n_neighbors) and

2) the distance metrics (p).

For feature selection, we use the powerful Random Forest Importance (RFI) method with 100 estimator. A trick here is that we need a bit iof coding so that we can make RFI feature selection as part of the pipline. For this reason, we define the custom RFIFeatureSelector() class below to pass in RFI as a "step" to the pipeline.

In [152]:
from sklearn.base import BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin
class RFIFeatureSelector(BaseEstimator, TransformerMixin):
    
    def __init__(self, n_features_=10):
        self.n_features_ = n_features_
        self.fs_indices_ = None
        
    def fit(self, cars_data, target):
        from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
        from numpy import argsort
        model_rfi = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100)
        model_rfi.fit(cars_data, target.ravel())
        self.fs_indices_= np.argsort(model_rfi.feature_importances_)[::-1][0:self.n_features_]
        return self 
    
    def transform(self, cars_data, target=None):
        return cars_data[:, self.fs_indices_]

Task 2.3: Neural Network Model Fitting & Tuning

Introduction¶

In this area, we are going examine the Neural Network (NN) show created for Cars Price prediction. The objective is to form an exact and vigorous show that can predict the costs of cars based on different highlights. We are going give a point by point outline of the NN model's topology, examine the pertinent demonstrate parameter values, and display the fine-tuning prepare with plots and clarifications.

Neural Network Topology:¶

The created NN demonstrate for Cars Cost Prediction comprises of numerous layers, counting input, covered up, and output layers. The topology is as takes after:

  • Input layer:

The responsibility of the input layer is to receive the feature inputs of automobiles, including details like brand, make, mileage, engine displacement, etc. The quantity of neurons in the input layer is established based on the count of input features within the given dataset.

  • Hidden Layers:

The concealed layers are accountable for acquiring intricate patterns and interconnections within the data. The hyperparameters that require adjustment include the quantity of obscured layers and the quantity of neurons contained within each layer.

  • Output Layer:

Using the learned patterns from the hidden layers, the output layer generates an estimation for car prices. The outcome of the Cars Price Prediction assignment involves a solitary neuron located in the output layer that represents the anticipated cost.

The relevant model parameter values¶

We optimized the NN model's performance by fine-tuning several hyperparameters. The hyperparameters were adjusted for optimal performance.

  • Number of Hidden Layers:

We conducted tests using various depths of hidden layers, including 1, 2, or 3, to determine the most effective depth for the network. The assessment of the performance was conducted using metrics such as Mean Absolute Error (MAE) or R2 score.

  • Batch Size:

The quantity of data samples employed in every iteration of the training procedure is determined by the batch size. We experimented with varying batch sizes, ranging from 32 to 128, to strike a balance between optimizing computational efficiency and achieving model convergence.

  • Learning Rate:

The learning rate determines the step size during the weight and bias update in the optimization process. We experimented with different learning rates, such as 0.001, 0.01, or 0.1, to find the value that leads to faster convergence and better performance.

  • Number of Neurons in Hidden Layers:

We experimented with different neuron quantities in the hidden layers to determine the ideal trade-off between model intricacy and effectiveness. Various neuron count configurations, including 16, 32, 64, or 128 neurons in every concealed layer, were experimented with.

  • Regularization Techniques:

Various regularization methods including L1 and L2 regularization, dropout, and early stopping were implemented to avoid overfitting and enhance generalization performance.

  • X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(data.drop('price', axis=1), data['price'], test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

  • scaler = MinMaxScaler() X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train) X_test_scaled = scaler.transform(X_test)

  • model model = Sequential() model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu', input_shape=(X_train_scaled.shape[1],))) model.add(Dense(64, activation='relu')) model.add(Dense(1, activation='linear'))

  • Compile the model model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001), loss='mean_squared_error')

  • Define early stopping criteria early_stopping = EarlyStopping(patience=10, restore_best_weights=True)

  • Train the model history = model.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train, validation_data=(X_test_scaled, y_test),

                  epochs=100, 
              batch_size=32, 
              callbacks=[early_stopping])
  • Evaluate the model test_loss = model.evaluate(X_test_scaled, y_test)

Model Comparison¶

During the hyper-parameter tuning phase above, we used the 3.5K rows in our training data within a cross-validation framework and we determined the best hyper-parameter values for each of the four regression model. For instance, for KNN, it turned out that the best set of the hyper-parameter values is k = 100 and p = 1 with the best 10 features as selected by the RFI feature selection method.

What we would like to do now is to 'fit' each tuned regressor ( with the best set of the hyper-parameter values) on the 1.5K rows in the test data in a cross-validated fashion to figure out which regressor model performs the best. This way, we would be measuring perfromance of the tuned regressor on data that they did not "see" previously.

Since cross validation itself is a random process, we would like to perfrom pariwise t-test to determined if any difference between the performance of any two regressor is statistically significant. Specifically, we first perfrom stratified cross-validation on each regressor where we use the same seed in each of the four cross-validation runs. Second, we conduct a paried t-test for the RMA and r2 score between the models.

Critique & Limitations

  • Our modelling strategy has certain shortcomings and limits. The decision for a black-box strategy, which prioritised raw prediction performance above interpretability, was one major restriction. Moving forwards, it would be useful to do a more thorough investigation of the feature selection and ranking process, as well as reconsider the hyper-parameter space selections. This would allow us to better balance predicted accuracy with the capacity to comprehend and evaluate the underlying reasons driving the projections.

  • We were limited in our modelling procedure to dealing with a small portion of the entire dataset in order to reduce the computing time necessary for training and testing. However, given the intrinsic importance of data, re-running our trials with the complete dataset while maintaining correct train and test split approach would be advantageous. This would result in a more complete and representative dataset, which might lead to enhanced model performance and more robust findings.

  • It would have been better to use the complete dataset for our model rather than just the top ten characteristics. We could obtain a more thorough depiction of the factors impacting automobile costs if we included the entire range of characteristics. This technique would most certainly improve the model's prediction skills and allow us to obtain a better grasp of the influence of various qualities on automobile costs.

  • The research concentrated specifically on measures that can be expressed numerically, such as the distance covered, motor capacity, and the duration since purchase of the auto. The analysis did not take into account certain qualitative factors including but not limited to the reputation of the brand, history of the vehicle and the preferences of the customer. Adding subjective elements can result in a more thorough comprehension of the dynamics of car prices and boost the precision of the models.

  • Because the RandomForestRegressor model outperformed the other three models in terms of statistical performance, we may look for ways to improve its predictive skills. One possible solution is to broaden the hyper-parameter search field, allowing for a more thorough examination of the model's parameter values. We may possibly increase the model's accuracy and fine-tune its behaviour to better suit the data by properly modifying the hyper-parameters, hence improving its overall performance.

Summary & Conclusions:

Project Summary:¶

During the initial phase of the project, we performed many data preparation procedures to assure the dataset's quality and integrity. Checking the data structure of the features to understand their kinds and formats was part of this. We also looked for missing numbers, duplicates, and outliers, all of which are frequent data quality concerns. We hoped to establish a clean and dependable dataset for further study by eliminating these concerns.

In addition, we performed exploratory data analysis (EDA) in the forms of univariate, bivariate, and multivariate analysis, concentrating on the correlations between the characteristics and the goal variable, which is the price. We were able to comprehend the distributions and statistics of individual attributes thanks to univariate analysis. Bivariate analysis assisted in identifying correlations between feature pairs and the target variable, giving light on possibly relevant associations. Multivariate research gave a more complete knowledge of how various factors interact with one another and impact automobile costs.

In the second part of the research, we concentrated on preprocessing strategies for categorical characteristics. We encoded the categorical features numerically for model training by employing appropriate approaches such as one-hot encoding or label encoding. We also performed feature scaling to ensure that all features were on the same scale, avoiding specific features from dominating the model's learning process due to their bigger magnitudes.

The procedures of feature selection and rating were critical in determining the most significant attributes for forecasting automobile costs. To identify the relevant characteristics, we used a variety of approaches such as statistical testing, feature importance from machine learning models, and correlation analyses. We were able to condense the model by picking a subset of significant characteristics, improving prediction performance and minimising computing complexity.

We investigated data sample approaches such as oversampling and undersampling to balance the representation of different classes in the dataset to address potential class imbalance. This stage aims to reduce bias in the model's predictions while also improving its capacity to generalise across multiple classes or categories.

We employed relevant machine learning methods for model implementation, such as Random Forest Regressor, KNN Regressor, Decision Tree, and regression models (Linear, Ridge, Lasso). These models were trained on the preprocessed dataset and their predictive ability was assessed using appropriate metrics such as mean squared error (MSE), root mean squared error (RMSE), or R-squared score.

We were conscious of the limits of the models and approaches used throughout the project. For example, we highlighted the possible computational complexity of certain models as well as the linearity and feature independence assumptions imposed by regression models. Understanding these constraints enabled us to more effectively analyse the models' results and predictions.

Summary of Findings: ¶

  • The RFI approach finds the most relevant characteristics, allowing the Random Forest model to focus on the factors that have the most influence when generating predictions.The Random Forest Regressor has a better r2 score, showing its capacity to successfully collect and generalise patterns in previously unexplored data.the entire dataset has the potential to reduce overfitting.Models trained on a bigger dataset may have superior convergence qualities and produce more consistent and interpretable results.

  • On the training data, the Random Forest Regressor with the top ten features chosen using the Random Forest Importance (RFI) technique has the greatest cross-validation r2 score. Furthermore, when tested on real-world data, the Random Forest Regressor outperforms the KNN Regressor, Decision Tree, and Regression models (Linear, Ridge, Lasso) in terms of r2 score. Working with the complete dataset, on the other hand, has the potential to minimise overfitting and provide models that are easier to train and comprehend.

Conclusions:¶

The study intends to uncover the essential factors that significantly contribute to forecasting automobile prices by analysing this information. The project attempts to give insights and assistance for used vehicle vendors and consumers by utilising machine learning models and data analysis approaches.

The case study intends to equip users with relevant information that may assist in making educated decisions about the price and purchase of used automobiles by meeting the objectives described above.In essence, the research strives to connect the dots among automotive industry, data analysis, and artificial intelligence models. By employing these methods, the project aims to equip users with an all-encompassing comprehension of the aspects that influence car prices, empowering them to make more informed pricing and purchasing choices.
